{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_paperflower_ver01/data/sn92070146/0041418859A/1930111501/0893.xml":{"full_text":"City and County News Briefs\nConservation Club to Meet \u2014A\nmeeting of the Conservation Club\nwill be held Monday, November 17\nat 7:30, in the clubrooms, 576 State.\nThe regular meeting scheduled lor\nthis week was postponed as it con\nflicted with the Armistice celebra\ntions.\nEaby Rice\u2014Buttered or sweeten\ned pop corn, always fresh. 5, 10\niml Hoc box. Next to Stage Depot.\nHtf\nAttend Hoitville Installation \u2014Mr\nand Mrs. P. A. Thaanum and Mrs.\nHarvey Kenyon were among the El\nCentrans attending the installation\nfor the Hoitville Legion. Thaanum\nacted as installing officer for the\npost and Mrs. Mattie Stewart ol\nImperial, for the Auxiliary unit.\nCONSUMPTION OF\nGRAPEFRUIT IS\nGROWING LARGER\nConsumption of grapefruit this\nyear indicates a marked increase\nover that of last year, according\nto Norman Lombard, manager of\nthe Desert Citrus exchange, who\nalso statps that consumption in a\ncomparatively early market in the\nPacific northwest is truly re\nmarkable. Moderately fair prices\nprevail, he said.\nExchange growers plan to ship\nbetween 2 and 25 cars during the\ncoming week and also the week\nfollowing.\nPresent consumption and market\nconditions, the manager explained,\nare a surprise to those in the mar\nketing industry up and down the\ncoast. Conditions are said to be\nbetter than any dared hope.\nCold nights are hastening the\ncoloring of the fruit and greatly\nincreasing the sugar and juice con\ntent, making the fruit of better\nquality. Warm days and nights\nprevalent during previous weeks\nhave retarded the developmi nt of\ncitrus fruits in the valley.\nHeavy volume in orange .ship\nments. according io Lombard, have\nnot affected local growers. Last\nyear's heavy orange distribution,\nhe concluded, did not affect the\nmarket nt all.\nSTOCK QUOTATIONS\nF. F N 92 1 s 93 T\nT. A. C. 16'. IfiV,\nI. C. T. 8' 9'h\nPotateT grower; in Klamath Coun\nty, Oregon, have had better control\nof potato diseases through the use\nof corrosive sublimate than with hot\nformaldehyde\nMake our Agency your\nINSURANCE STORE\nAll lines\u2014Completely Equipped plant\u2014Convenient\nlocation\u2014Experienced and competent service.\nHerbert Lowdermilk\nGENERAL INSURANCE\nPhone 1294 626 Main Street El Centro\nArcade Theatre\nHOLTVILLE\nStarting tonight at 11:30 p. in., and continuing Sun\nday, Monday and Tuesday. Attend the Matinee\nSunday afternoon at 2:30.\nOUT OF THE HEAVENS\nONTO THE SCREEN!\n*o*\nX. 3\nSpring Into\nGlamorous Life\nBefore the Eyes\nof Millions!\nIK.\n9\n\n\nr\n1 Sue Carol\nIrene Rich\nRaif Harold*\npoHS!\nCharles Morton\nDuke Ellington\nand Ills Band\nin\ncmK\n<HE(K\nin All Stur\nSupporting Cast\nA MEL BROWN\nProduction\nStory hy UmJ\nBert Kalmar\nHarry Ruby\ns'tiiiJLi\n\u2014The Characters Who\nHave Made Twenty Mil\nlion Radios Throb with\nLife in Their First Fea\nture Picture!\nFiles Suit Suit to recover\n$1050.96 alleged due them on a\npromisory note, the Central Bank of\nImperial Valley yesterday afternoon\nnamed A. Liera and Aurelia G.\nLiera as defendants.\nDr. A, B. Hanson, Dentist, Davis\nBldg. Extraction specialist.\nDr. Harry Hooper Dentist, 110\nNorth Gth St. l\u2019hone 382\nStudents Visit Library\u2014Students\nof the Eastside high school visited\nthe city labrary recently, Miss Agnes\nFerris, city librarian, instructing\nthem in the proper use of the libra\nry so that it could be of the great\nest service to them.\nBAPTISTS CLOSE\nSUCCESSFUL MEET\nThe Imperial Valley Baptist As\nsociation closed its annual session\nlast night at the Baptist church in\nBrawley. It was a two days\u2019 ses\nsion. The gathering was attended\nby delegates from the Baptist\nchurches of the valley and from\nBlythe. A fine program was car\nried out.\nThose attending as delegates\nirom the local church were Mr.\nand Mrs. J. W. King, Mr. and Mrs.\nC. W. Whisler, Rev. and Mrs. C.\nE. Flanagin, Mrs. Vera Harris,\nMrs. Jennie Jones, Mrs. J. C. Riv\nes, Mrs. Cora Earl, Mrs. L. A. Dun\nlap, Mrs. Charles Forsberg, Mrs.\nAnna Lewis, Mrs. H. E. Corkbill,\nMrs. G. W. Finley. Mrs. Ruth Blo\nemsma, Mr. and Mrs. Benson. El\nCentro was chosen as the place of\ni jeeting for next year.\nRev. G. Manley was elected as\nmoderator for the coming year.\nRev. C. E. Flanagin was elected\nadvisory member of the state con\nvention board and Mrs. C. E. Flan\nagin was appointed by the state\nboard as secretary director of the\nWoman's Missionary Work of the\nAssociation.\nFew Cases In\nPolice Court\nAfter the heavy business of the\npast few days, Judge Kendall B\nPerkins of the city court today had\na light docket.\nOnly four prisoners were brought\nbefore\u2019 him. and three of the cases\nwere continued until Monday. The\ncase against J. W. Henderson, 18,\ncharged with vagrancy, was dis\nmissed.\nTo appear in court Monday are\nJ C. Roberts, 23, vagrancy; D. S.\nBerrwell. 21, vagrancy, and George\nMeagher, 20, investigation.\nIMPERIAL. VALLEY PRESS. EL CENTRO CALIFORNIA. SATURDAY. NOVEMBER 15, 1930\nHemstitching and covered but\ntons. Mrs. Wilson, 1323 Broad\nway.. 20tf\nAnother Big Dance at Mt. Signal\nSaturday night, Nov. 15. Good mu\nsic. Bt7\nIntend to Marry\u2014Notice of in\ntention to marry was filed with the\ncounty clerk yesterday afternoon by\nAlejandro G. Colio, 34, and Lauren\ntia Molina, 30, of Calexico.\nMarriage License issued\u2014A mar\nriage license was issued today to\nLuis Valdez, 26, and Margaritu Mar\ntinez, 23, both of Brawley.\nFiles Complaint\u2014A criminal com\nplaint against S. N. Ramirez was\nfiled today with Judge I. Mayfield\nwith C. C. Ewing as complaining\nwitness. Ewing stated he had been\ndischarged by Ramirez, and that the\nlatter refused to pay him his wages\nFine Linens, Table Silver and\nfine glassware for sale for Thanks\ngiving and Christmas gifts. Prices\nat a fraction of real value; goods\nnever used. Phone 619 after 5 p.\nm. w-sat.\nCharged With Grand Theft-\nFrank Robertson, 34, was in jail to\nday charged with grand theft. Ro\nbertson was arrested on the com\nplaint of J. C. Poe, who charged\nhim with the theft of a large num\nber of chickens.\nFirst Cold Days\u2014Check up your\nWOOD supply and Phone 1, Pioneer\nTruck and Transfer Co. for service.\nTu-Th-Sat\nCOURT DEFERS\nMOTION TO SET\nASIDE DEFAULT?\nJudge Vaughn Thompson yester\nday afternoon continued the hear\ning on a motion to set aside de\nfault in the case of William Caine\nDavidson until next Friday.\nH. I. Mulcrevy and Thomas l inn,\ndefendants, entered the motion to\nset aside default, asserting that de\nfault had been entered against\nthem by surprise, inadvertance and\nexcusable neglect.\nThis occurred when Davidson\u2019s\nattorney dismissed the case against\nnumerous other defendants, in\ncluding Matthew Brady, San Fran\ncisco district attorney, entering de\nfault against Mulcrevy and Finn.\nDavidson was suing for $1,000,000\ndamages, charging false arrest.\nHe was arrested, he asserted in\nhis complaint, so that he could not\nrive testimony oeiore the house of\nrepresentatives sub-committee re\ngarding illegal liquor traffic and\nthe connection of certain banks\nwith that traffic.\nIn an affidavit opposing the mo\ntion to set aside default Davidson\nclaimed tlrut both Mulcrevy and\nFinn had been duly served with\nprocess and summons, and that\ntheir failure to appear before the\ncourt on the date set for hearing\nwas due te \"inexcusable neglect\nand ignoring and defying process\nand summons.\nMulcrevy, in his position as coun\nty clerk of San Francisco, was\nfully aware of the effect and pen\nalty attendant upon the failure of\na defendant to appear in court, as\nserted Davidson in his affidavit.\nNo agreement was made between\nthe plaintiff and th\" defendant re\ngarding an extension of time,\nclaimed Davidson. He pointed out\nthat the defendants signed a mo\ntion for change of venue, and that\ntherefore they were aware of the\ncase against them,\nThere was at no lime any mis\ntake, inadvertance, surprise or ex\ncusable neglect in the case, claimed\nthe plaintiff.\ns>\nTHE WEATHER\nLos Angeles arcl Vicinity In\ncreasing cloudiness with rain late\ntonight and Sunday; somewhat\nhigher temperature tonight; mod\nerate to fresh southerly winds to\nnight and Sunday.\nSouthern California Cloudy\ncast and rain late tonight or Sun\nday west portion; warmer tonight:\nlresh southerly winds offshore.\nlocal Weather\nFORECAST BY F. A. BAI MAN\nU. S. Weather Bureau\nMinimum this morning\nMaximum yesterday\n42\n67\nGuernsey Breeder\nExpert Due Monday\nC. W. Robinson of tile Guernsey\nBreeders' Association will arrive in\nEl Centro on Monday and will spend\nthe next few days with various\nbreeders in the valley.\nH. G. Farnsworth has called a\nmeeting for Monday evening at 8\no'clock in the farm advisor's office,\nat which time all those interested in\nbringing into the county pure bred\nstock arc urged to be present.\nSALES-EXECUTIVE WANTED\nAND NEEDED\nA client of ours (in the financial\nbusiness) has asked us to procure a\nhigh-class Sales-Executive in El\nCentro\u2014a man capable of hand\nling salesmen. He must be a seas\noned executive of integrity a\nman worthy to represent a success\nful organization and able to pro\nduce effectively. A real opportun\nity for the right man. Write, state\nyour experience, qualifications, age,\nwith references, to\nForest Johnston A Associates,\n1039 W. Washington St. fats Angeles\nNEW CHEVROLET\nMODELS SHOWN\nFOR FIRST TIME\n\u25a0v\nChevrolet's new car for 1931,\npriced substantially below current\nlevels, goes on display today\nthroughout the nation.\nHeralded as \u201cThe Great American\nj Value,\u201d the new car boasts a two\ninch increase in wheelbase, larger\nand roomier bodies by Fisher with\nmohair or broadcloth as optional\ntrimming, and scores of refine\nments in appearance and perform\nance despite the new price which\nbrings the level for the 1931 car to\na far lower figure than any Chev\nrolet, four or six, has ever sold.\nDealers throughout the United\nStates put the new models on exhi\nbition this morning for the first\ntime, nearly two months in advance\nof the customary date for the show\ning of the annual new car. This\nmove in advancing the announce\nment. date, it was felt by Chevrolet\nofficials, would render a distinct\ncontribution to the cause of general\nbusiness revival by insuring extra\nordinary activity during two nor\nmally dull business months for the\n200.000 people throughout the Unit\ned States who depend directly upon\nChevrolet for their livelihood.\nThe 19 domestic production plants\nof the Chevrolet organization are\nnow in full swing on the new model,\naccording to W. S. Knudsen, presi\ndent, and shipments are going out\nto dealers to assure immediate de\nlivery of all models.\nFundamentally the new model\nembodies the same basic features\nwhich, since the introduction of the\nChevrolet Six, enabled it to achieve\na popularity four times as great as\nany other six cylinder car. How\never, scores of improvements and\nrefinements have been made this\nyear\u2014every change designed to in\ncrease the smartness, performance,\nsafety or durability of this latest\nGeneral Motors model.\nMany Improvements\nAmong the improvements are a\nfully insulated front compartment,\neasier steering, more durable clutch,\nsmoother and quieter transmission,\nand liberal use of rustless chromium\nplate on exposed bright parts. Four\nLovejoy hydraulic shock absorbers,\nand fully enclosed, waterproof lour\nwheel brakes continue as standard\nequipment.\nIn the line of nine body types are\nthree open models \u2014the roadster,\nphaeton and sport roadster, and six\nclosed models\u2014the coach, sedan,\nspecial sedan, the three-window\ncoupe, and five-window coupe, and\nthe sport coupe.\nAll sport models come equipped\nwith the new and popular chrome\nplated radiator grills. All models\nhave smart new wire wheels, with\n4.75 by 19 tires as standard equip\nment. Hubs are very large, of the\nconcealed bolt type, with hub caps\nof gleaming chromium plate set oli\nby a block ring circling the Chev\nrolet emblem in the center. Wheel\nfinishes harmonize with the wide\nvariety of body combinations.\nEvery change and new feature has,\nmet and survived innumerable tests\nbefore being incorporated in the\n1931 car. Consistent with the estab\nlished policy of \"working two years\nahead.\u201d the Chevrolet engineering\ndepartment was at work on this new\ncar before the public showing of\nlast year\u2019s model. Each one of the\n20 major engineers has been at work\non various units, oftentimes two or\nmore engineers working indepen\ndently on the same unit.\nEntirely apart from Chevrolet\u2019s\nown engineers and designers were\nfurther facilities for the develop\nment of the car in the General Mo\ntors Research Laboratories, the most\nextensive project of its kind in the\nindustry, and in the large corps o!\nexpert craftsmen of the Fisher Body\norganization. The combined talent\nof these vast organizations has been\nbrought to bear on the new 1931\nChevrolet that it might measure up\nto its slogan of \u2019\u2019The Great Ameri\ncan Value.\"\nItems Of News\nAbout Town\nMrs. .Luther Wilson was down\nfrom Brawley today on a shopping\nexpedition.\nAmong the shoppers here today\nwas Mrs. Fred Talcher. who came\ndown from her home in Brawley.\nMrs. Marcia Farrell and Mrs,\nEdith Cameron are in Los Angeles\nattending a course of study for state\nAuxiliary officers.\nMr. and Mrs. Coy Van Doren\nMiss Edith Allen, all of La Mesa,\nand Dorwin Baker of El Cajon, are\nweek-end guests of the Misses Mar\ngaret and Mildred Giles.\nW. S. Fawcett has returned from\na trip to Los Angeles.\nSome Of Auto\u2019s\nParts Missing\nSome Imperial Valley motorist to\nday was without his running board\nand rear fenders as a result ol a\ncollision last night on the Brawley\nImperial highway half a mile south\nof the 101 Ranch.\nO. L. Slaughter, driving a truck\nwas struck by a motorist in a coupe,\nwhose car slid along the side ol the\ntruck, leaving the running board\nand the fender, and puncturing the\nlire of the truck. The motorist did\nnot stop.\nThe affair was reported to the\nstate traffic office by Slaughter.\nLEARNED HIS LESSON\nHOLLYWOOD. Nov. 15. U.R>\u2014An\nunideptified man dropped in to see\n\u201cThe Bad Man\u201d at the Mar-Cal\nTheater last night. On his way out\nhe stopped at the box office, thrust\na gun in the face of Miss Clara\nBerg, cashier, and took SO6.\nHe re ts 9 31m ode Is, announced today. The new cars have many improvements and refine\nments throughout. The cars are longer, more powerful and speedier. At the upper left is the At the upper\nright is a girl pointing to the new radiator grille, chromium plated, which is standard equipment on all new Chevrolet\nSport Models. At the lower left is the Sedan. At the lower right is the sport roadster, with the top down. The new\nmodels are on disnlav today at the Chevrolet agency here.\nMay Ship 900\nCars Of Peas\nPea shipments from Imperial\nValley this season total 343 car\nleads and it is estimated that there\nare more than 500 carloads yet to\nroll.\nPotential yield is estimated at\napproximately SOO cars.\nThe season may continue until\nwell along in December provided\nthe frost does not interefere.\nPeas are selling 15 cents a pound\nwholesale in eastern markets which\nindicates that they are selling for\n20 and 25 cents a pound retail.\nThe sixth annua! California wool\nshow was held at South San Fran\ncisco, October 27-29. at the stock\nyards while the junior livestock\nshow was on.\nJmAJ2s oj^icyclijlh\nOF STRIKING BEAUTY\nThe now Fortl de luxe bodies are offered in addition to the standard Ford line. They have met with\ngreat favor because of their striking lines and the quiet richness of upholstery, trimming and appointments.\nHigh quality is evident in every detail. Call or phone for demonstration.\n!l;j^\n\nL_Jl\n0\nIP\nTHE NEW FORD DE LUXE PHAETON\nDistinguished by its low, fleet lines, and attractive sport treatment. One\nwide door admits to front and rear seats. Driver's scat is adjustable.\nSeat and back cushions are upholstered in genuine leather. Triplex\nshatter-proof glass windshield and windshield wings fold flat. Cowl lights,\nside fender-well, trunk rack and front and rear bumpers ure standard\nequipment.\nNEW FORD DE LUXE ROADSTER\nA sttjxino sport car. Finished in Haven Hlack, Washington Blue, and\nStone Brown, with steel-spoke wheels in a harmonizing color. Seat and\nhack cushions (except rumble seat) upholstered in genuine leather. Dis\ntinctive tan top has natural wood bows. Humble seat, cowl lights, trunk\nrack, side fender-well for spare wheel, and front and rear bumpers are\nstandard equipment.\n\u25a0T' s\nA\nIP Vi fM\n\nV-3\nA\nV\nat\nW i\n10033\nr~\nz- (mw\n''\u00ae'U\n-2\u00b1isa\nNEW FORD DE LUXE COUPE\nWons will be quick to note the rich interior of this beautiful c!o t\ncar. You may choose upholstery of brown mohair or Bedford cord. Ifard\nwarc is of distinctive scroll design. Dome light and cowl lights ure stand\nard equipment. Selection in body colors includes Maroon, Kcwanee\nGreen, Chide Drab and Black. Seat adjudable.\nNEW FORD DE LUXE SEDAN\nA striking EXAsinr of the rich finish that characterizes all of these new\nFord de luxe bodies. For upholstery you may choose either fashionable\nBedford cord or luxurious mohair. Driver's seat is adjustable. Wide\n.rear seat has a folding center arm rest and side arm rests. Cowl lights\narc standard equipment. There is a wide variety of body colors.\n-joriiT\n-4\nEH\nSjh\nv;\nm\nAuthorized FORD Dealers\n\n4\nChevrolet Announces New Six for 1931\nILLNESS FATAL TO\nWOLFORD\u2019S FATHER\nA telegram received today in the\ndistrict attorney's office here gave\nthe information that the father of\nI). H. Wolford, deputy district at\ntorney. died yesterday in Hot\nSprings, New Mexico.\nWolford's father was 63 years old\nHe had been ill for some time. Ac\ncording to members of the district\nattorney's staff here, the old man\nliad been an attorney at law in New\nMexico for many years.\nWolford is in Hot Springs, and\nwill attend the funeral of his father\nSTRICKLER FLORAL\nCOMPANY OPENED\nFormal opening of the Strickler\nFloral Company's new shop began\nat noon today and will continue\nthrough Sunday, the public being!\ncordially invited to visit ine hand\nsome store at 510 South Sixth street. I\n\nM. T. Haul, proprietor of the soit j\ndrink stand at the Pickwick stage\ndepot, who is famous for his delici- 1\nous lemonade, announces that he I\nwill serve lemonade on this occasion j\nto all those visiting the store.\nCharcoal Broiler\nThe only one in Imperial alley.\nCFIOPS \u2014STEAKS \u2014CHICKEX LOBSTERS\nCooked the way you like them.\nCITY LIMITS CAFE\nCorner Imperial and San Diego Highway\n3\nHAVEKORST\nGUERNSEY FARMS\nNow have available Golden\nGuernsey Raw \u201cGuaranteed\nMilk\u201d\np Phone El Centro 546","height":"29548","width":"23276"}}
